description.narrative: Output 3.6: ParticipationParticipation of children and adolescents in decisions that affect their lives, including in civic engagement initiatives and mechanisms, is improved, in targeted areas., which contributes to Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement, Learning, Skills, Participation And Engagement (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Communications, Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Learning and protectionBy 2022, more vulnerable children, adolescents and youth experience improved learning and are increasingly protected from violence, abuse, exploitation and neglect.

description.narrative: In 2021, UNICEF reached;52,197;young people through multiple;initiatives;to improve their participation and transition from learning to earning focusing on addressing the negative impacts of COVID-19.;31,700;(18.7% refugees/migrants, 49.5% girls) young people (10-24) were reached through Meshwary programme in partnership with the Ministry of Youth and Sports (MOYS). Additional;4,277;(8% refugees/migrants, 88.7% girls) adolescents (10-18) participated in UNICEF’s Sports for Development programme, focused on social cohesion and girls’ empowerment; and;16,220;young people participated in civic engagement and volunteering initiatives.;1,720;youth from 57 universities and Meshwary were trained to deliver life-skills training in underserved communities. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:29/12/2021
